******
[2] Cholera - Venezuela (Venezuelan Capital District) ex Cuba
Date: Fri 9 Aug 2013
Source: El Universal [in Spanish, machine trans., summ., edited]
http://www.eluniversal.com/vida/130808/reportan-dos-casos-de-colera-en-el-pais


The Venezuelan Society of Public Health reported that there are the 2 people infected with cholera in the country. In its statement the medical society indicated that the 2 people are a couple who had traveled in Cuba and returned to the country this week. They add that the disease has been confirmed by laboratory and that patients are hospitalized in a private clinic in the capital.

"Unofficially, we know that on 7 Aug 2013, 2 cases of cholera imported from Cuba were identified. They were laboratory confirmed and both are hospitalized in private clinics in eastern Caracas. The couple returned from Havana, Cuba, and symptoms began with acute, copious diarrhea requiring hospitalization on 6 Aug 2013. Cultures were reported positive for _Vibrio cholerae_ the next day.

[byline: Carolina Contreras]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[An interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Venezuela can be found at http://healthmap.org/r/7ZSN.

In 1991, cholera spread to Latin America, which had been free of cholera for more than a century. The disease spread rapidly, causing nearly 400 000 reported cases and over 4000 deaths in 16 countries of the Americas in 1991. By the end of 1993, nearly a million cases were reported and almost 9000 people died. In those 3 years, the epidemic affected all the countries of Latin America except Uruguay and the Caribbean. The organism was initially introduced into Peru and genetic analysis suggested that the source was Africa (Lam C, Octavia S, Reeves P, Wang L, Lan R. Evolution of seventh cholera pandemic and origin of 1991 epidemic, Latin America. Emerg Infect Dis. 2010; 16(7): 1130-2; http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3321917/). The epidemic in Latin America lasted until the end of the decade. The inadequate public health/sanitary infrastructure in Latin America fed the flames of this epidemic as it did more recently in Haiti. Protection of a safe potable water supply is needed to prevent a repeat in Latin America.

It is not stated where in Cuba the Chilean patient had traveled but the temporal clustering with the Venezuelan couple suggests the possibility that the 3 may have traveled together. - Mod.LL]
